{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651752"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18489"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18489"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.63,0.08,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79938"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11218"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6994"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26274"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79938"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the autonomic nerve supply to the midgut?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parasympathetic fibres from both vagal and sacral sources","Sympathetic fibres from thoracic segments and parasympathetic fibres from vagus nerve","Sympathetic fibres from lumbar segments","Parasympathetic fibres from sacral segments","Sympathetic fibres from cervical segments"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe midgut receives dual autonomic innervation via the superior mesenteric plexus. \u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic fibres from thoracic segments and parasympathetic fibres from vagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because the parasympathetic supply comes from the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) while sympathetic fibres originate from thoracic spinal cord segments T5-T12.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParasympathetic fibres from both vagal and sacral sources\u003C/strong\u003E - The midgut only receives parasympathetic input from the vagus nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic fibres from lumbar segments\u003C/strong\u003E - Lumbar sympathetic fibres supply the hindgut, not the midgut\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParasympathetic fibres from sacral segments\u003C/strong\u003E - Sacral parasympathetic fibres supply the hindgut, not the midgut\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic fibres from cervical segments\u003C/strong\u003E - Cervical sympathetic fibres supply structures in the head, neck and upper thorax\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese autonomic nerves travel along the superior mesenteric artery to supply midgut derivatives from the second part of the duodenum to the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superior mesenteric plexus provides sympathetic and parasympathetic innervation to midgut derivatives from the second part of the duodenum to the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon.","Parasympathetic fibres in the superior mesenteric plexus originate from the vagus nerve.","Sympathetic fibres in the superior mesenteric plexus originate from thoracic spinal segments T5-T12."],"r